03856nam a22005775i 9780822376972DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223769727 a10.1515/97808223769722doi  a(DE-B1597)551761  a(OCoLC)871709130  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aN72.S6bG37213 2014 7aART0090002bisacsh04a701/.032231 aGarcía Canclini, Néstor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArt beyond Itself :bAnthropology for a Society without a Story Line /cNéstor García Canclini. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (232 p.) :b22 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tPREFACE Art beyond Itself -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Aesthetics and Social Sciences -- t2. Visual Cultures -- t3. Reappropriating Objects -- t4. Putting a Value on Art -- t5. Unsure Localizations -- t6. The Death of Public Space -- t7. How Society Makes Art -- tEPILOGUE -- tWORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFirst published in Spanish in 2010, Art beyond Itself is Néstor García Canclini's deft assessment of contemporary art. The renowned cultural critic suggests that, ideally, art is the place of imminence, the place where we glimpse something just about to happen. Yet, as he demonstrates, defining contemporary art and its role in society is an ever more complicated endeavor. Museums, auction houses, artists, and major actors in economics, politics, and the media are increasingly chummy and interdependent. Art is expanding into urban development and the design and tourism industries. Art practices based on objects are displaced by practices based on contexts. Aesthetic distinctions dissolve as artworks are inserted into the media, urban spaces, digital networks, and social forums. Oppositional artists are adrift in a society without a clear story line. What, after all, counts as transgression in a world of diverse and fragmentary narratives? Seeking a new analytic framework for understanding contemporary art, García Canclini is attentive to particular artworks; to artists including Francis Alÿs, León Ferrari, Teresa Margolles, Antoni Muntadas, and Gabriel Orozco; and to efforts to preserve, for art and artists, some degree of independence from religion, politics, the media, and the market.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aAesthetics, Moderny21st century. 0aArt and anthropology. 0aArt and society. 0aPostmodernism. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aFrye, David08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376972zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376972423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376972.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles